Eigenvectors are very specific to a matrix. Multiplying a matrix
\emph{A} with \emph{e\textsubscript{1}} returns the first column of
\emph{A}. That is, if \emph{aj} is the \emph{j}-th column of \emph{A},

\begin{align*}
A = \begin{bmatrix}
a_1 & | & a_2 & | & \dots & | & a_n
\end{bmatrix}
\end{align*}

then

\begin{align*}
Ae_1 = \begin{bmatrix}
a_1 & | & a_2 & | & \dots & | & a_n
\end{bmatrix}e_1 = a_1
\end{align*}

Since \emph{v = e\textsubscript{1}} is an eigenvector of the matrix
\emph{A} we know that

\begin{align*}
Av &= \lambda v \\
Ae_1 &= \lambda e_1 = \begin{bmatrix} \lambda \\ 0 \\ \vdots \\ 0 \end{bmatrix}
\end{align*}

Hence \emph{a\textsubscript{1} = $\lambda$ e\textsubscript{1}}. In other words,
the only non-zero entry of the first column of \emph{A} is in the first
row. Can you perform elementary row operations to move that entry into
another row, and hence find a counter example?
